text: i think this movie wins because of its cast and subject matter, but many of the scenes fail to shake a sense of parody even as they try to appear genuine.  Whoever wrote and directed this, they don't seem to have dug into the material in a way that differs from the opportunists in the film. Speaking of the opportunists, there are no good guys in this movie, everybody in this film is guilty of fraud.  Seriously, it doesn't matter where "the law" draws the lines of, "concionable investment."  If you buy insurance with the expectation of default, that's fraudulent.    I think the only real honest living there is, is when you live off your own product with your own work.  In "civilized society" there is no such thing as an "honest living."  We all pick our product off the backs of people we've never met.  We don't care where it comes from, and if we do, we can't really know where it comes from; we just take what we can get with electronic blood paper.  But we all die, so it evens out in the end.

text: Well, I guess it's the right year for a left-wing propaganda piece.  Government regulation sets the rules.  Banks follow the rules.  If you don't like the results, shrink government, deregulate the markets, allow interstate competition, and use the power of the private citizens' purses to force companies to compete.  Competition drives down prices and hikes up quality.  The ridiculous volatility of the housing market, auto market, stock market, etc is the result of massive regulations.  Those massive regulations are too confusing for the 300 million laypeople in America to understand, and we're forced to put our money into markets we don't want to be in to avoid the government stealing huge portions of our earnings through taxation.  This movie will be absolutely filled with misinformation.  There should be a movie made about the crash, but it should be honest.  This is a real bummer.

text: People who enjoy this movie are the same people who believed the housing market would not crash. This movie like the housing market was setup on a good premise. The idea of both this movie and mortgages were good ideas. But neither would made a bunch of money. So now we need to make money. Lets add in a super cast to support the movie and add mortgage bonds and cdo to give it a bigger appeal.  Now we need to add in completely irreverent side stories, brother killing himself, love interest and random friends that further complicate things. Likewise in the mortgage business lets add in synthetic cdos because the original deals weren't lucrative enough.  Now we need an agency to rubber stamp the cdo so that we don't lose money.  Likewise we need advertisement hype machine saying this is an awesome movie so that it too doesn't lose money.  Now we need to make sure the buyer/viewer feels like they understand it. We'll lightly go over the smallest points so that they feel smart and important. Hot tub scene, casino scene  and interview with exec at restaurant to name a few.  Likewise with the mortgage the brokers would explain how stable it was, how much money they could make without actually going into depth.  This movie is either the biggest insult to the viewer or one of smarter films to directly mimic in structure the story it's trying to tell.
